Parliament did not support the amendment liberating Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament has rejected a proposal to repeal a section of the criminal code that convicted opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment, which would pave the way for the release of the imprisoned former prime minister, was rejected by MPs at the second reading of the proposal to commute sentences for economic crimes.
Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly disadvantageous contract with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The sentence is not final, the appeal of the convicted person is due to be heard by the court in December.
Tymoshenko called the verdict a political vendetta against the regime, and suspicions of bias prompted the trial in the West.
The proposal to remove Section 365 from the Criminal Code, on the basis of which the former prime minister was convicted, was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
It took 226 votes to pass.
