Diet of an obese child: does not eat breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with being overweight, with 9% of schoolchildren being overweight, and 5% of children being obese.
Obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to a recent survey.
Again, it shows how important the environment in which a person grows up and the patterns with which he is surrounded are for healthy development.
For example, sausages appear on the tables of obese children up to half as often as in families of children with normal weight.
Fried fries had dinner the day before the research related to the awareness-raising event called Obesity is no coincidence more than 19 percent of obese.
In fat families, it is also not customary to play sports, but this applies to most families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of children responded that their parents find time to exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of the Obesity is Not a Coincidence event, which is supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 pupils from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Eating right and getting enough exercise in the family is one of the determinants of dramatically increasing numbers of children who are overweight or even obese.
“For example, only half of those surveyed reported eating breakfast-lunch-lunch-dinner-five times a day, which is one of the basic prerequisites for proper nutrition,” reads one of the survey results.
Without breakfast and evening sausage
Experts point out that relative details, such as regular family breakfast times, are also essential for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of schoolchildren’s families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing is that 10 percent of households don’t eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a proper daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families of obese children are much more likely to eat unhealthy fries.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent).
More than 40 percent of children regularly play sports, but the result for their parents was less than half - 15 percent.
Assemble your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to build their own diet according to their own tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite foods are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes.
"The great popularity of sugary lemonades is particularly alarming," the survey's final report said.
For lunch, pasta won over poultry.
But the children practically did not want legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and midday vegetable dishes is also low.
Move to health
The research also showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"The control group of survey participants who filled out the questionnaire after the end of the education lecture Obesity is not a coincidence, in a number of cases there was a significant shift of preferences towards the principles of healthy diet," the results of the project say.
This was especially true with sweet lemonades, where more children would start to prefer plain water.
Children were also much more likely to check poultry and fish as the main meal of the day and would cut back on sweet foods and dumplings.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say professionals
In the introductory article on how stylists learn, I complained a little bit that there was already a lot in the introductory lessons.
I had no idea what was coming next.
Lectures of three professionals from the field, dressing problematic characters and a seminar on how it goes on the set.
And it gets worse.
The closer to the final exam, the more information and practical tasks await us.
And even though the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it is really "footstepped".
This time we discussed with the director Alice (there is not a single boy in the course) how to dress a woman who does not have a perfectly symmetrical figure.
And those are the vast majority.
Someone has a short neck, someone has a boyish figure without proper curves, and someone is overweight.
The stylist must know how to visually soften the broad shoulders, lengthen the neck or deliver the necessary curves.
We were given tips, such as for a woman like Jennifer Lopez, i.e. bigger breasts and hips and a narrow waist, to emphasize the figure nicely and at the same time not dress the woman too provocatively.
For example, if the difference between the waist and hips is such that the skirts or pants really do not fit, then it is worth having at least one such piece tailor-made.
You will definitely not regret it, because perfectly fitting clothes are priceless.
In a tailored skirt you will feel much better than in one that constantly shifts, rolls up, stays in the waist and so on.
The boy figure can also afford to wear clothes with creases, applications, embroidery or scooping.
Of course, there is a lot of such information and types of characters, so I am glad that I have a whole week to sort out all the information in my head.
And I'm still worried that given the homework assignment, it's too much.
Each of the students was assigned a celebrity, who has to come up with two outfits: daytime and evening.
We have to take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the person and the type of character.
I'll "dress" Miranda Kerr, you may know her from Victoria's Secret campaigns.
I’m cheering, for me personally definitely better than Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who has recently gained maybe a hundred pounds (please take into account exaggeration), or young Selena Gomez.
Clothes must be cut from magazines or searched on the Internet and printed and then graphically processed.
Moodboard, as the whole result is called, then express our personal style and relationship to graphic design.
It is also important to think about the graphic side of styling.
The stylist does not only dress physically, but also creates, for example, so-called product pages in magazines (for specific assignments, such as trendy handbags, coats, etc.).
The stylist and designer Mario Kameník told us about this.
But that's not until Sunday.
The stylist must have a general overview
Saturday's lecture packed with information about the types of characters was enriched by three guests from the field.
Stylist Honza Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and the stylist should be able to take advantage of it.
And a handy stylist can work with one piece of clothing in different ways.
Variability is key in this case.
For example, such a trench coat (or, if you want, originally a trenchcoat) can be worn classically over jeans and a T-shirt as a coat, but you can also dress it on a bare body, put on pumps and take pictures as a dress.
Or just roll up your sleeves or collars and the whole look looks different.
“Play with it,” he emphasized.
But what I appreciated the most was the following advice: "To work you need to know the rules perfectly."
"Then you can start breaking them," said Jacob.
Finally, I understand why we are crushing all the precepts, what to combine with, what to do, why, when we sometimes see something else in fashion magazines.
Not to mention the parades.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I know that the stylist has to have many more variants of clothes prepared than how many of them can be photographed.
So in a fashion story that has ten pages (ten outfits), I have to be ready to “steal” at least fifteen.
And also that in the photo clothes look and work in combination with other pieces sometimes completely different than in reality.
This is what we need to consider when creating an outfit.
Honza Pokorný confirmed to us that image and style makes sometimes up to half of success.
Just look at Madonna, who is not exactly a miracle singer, but her image and marketing have made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the approach to using the services of stylists is rather cold.
Even the familiar faces sometimes consider it useless (it is enough that I know something, the way I look is secondary).
And if someone lets us create styling, then we should count on the fact that he will most likely dictate to us a completely different (smaller) size than he really should.
Then you have to Google and see if the tabloids did not write about the fact that the celebrity has become fat / thin and so on.
On Sunday, both Jan and Mario told us that it is not enough for the stylist to orient himself in fashion and to be able to put together an outfit.
In his work, he primarily communicates with the people he dresses, so it is important to be a good psychologist.
Being able to guess people, not pandering, standing up for your opinion.
"If a manager orders you to sort through her closet and complete it with nice pieces, you can't just throw out the whole closet and say, 'Oh, my God, that's terrible.'"
“Find at least a few things to compliment and recommend what they can be worn for,” says Mario.
He also specifically showed us what the so-called "placovka", or bag for the set, must contain.
It's the one you put around your waist and have all the props you need.
In addition to bright things such as scissors, hair roller or safety pins, there is also a nylon thread (with it the stylist helps to take pictures of products such as handbags or hats), special clips that we clip on the back of clothes if it is larger (a pin or other clamp is not allowed, it would damage the garment), or a sew-on.
In order not only not to listen, but also to practically try something, we learned how to properly fit shoes.
Even when shooting in a studio where there is a flat surface, the sole could be damaged, let alone outside.
And so we glued and glued.
The shoes must not be touched with scissors so that they do not accidentally get damaged.
So there is a real need for skill.
Mario delighted me when he praised my creation without reservation.
This skill is not really my friend.
This is just a small fraction of what we heard on the second weekend of the course.
It is becoming more and more clear to me that it is really not a walk in the park, no matter who wants what.
Need for Speed: The Run is a race across America.
Reviews
Originally carefree driving due to a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes turns into a routine morning trip on the shift.
The ambition was largely achieved, but it is of no use if no one clearly wanted to do anything extra.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run raised high expectations before its release.
He promised that the long-running Need for Speed racing series would once again take a piece in a new direction, and from playable demonstrations appeared as a game that would not be in the genre of action racing only to the number.
We were also curious how the inserted passages will turn out, in which the main character gets out of the car and runs on his own.
However, as usual with the NFS series, many things are a bit different than we expected.
These are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have appeared in the series more or less for several years.
So these are not actually mistakes, but rather a manifestation of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal nature and as a solution offers to participate in an illegal race across America.
Get behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York.
The idea brings with it some interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
It doesn’t feel like the game is always offering the same thing.
Some of the environments are also very nice to look at, even though the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's not world-class.
But driving through the desert, autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains looks visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are enriched from time to time by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you have to be careful not to be covered by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are quite well planted.
There are only a few, but that’s enough.
For a while you are trying to overtake the required number of opponents (essentially a classic race), then you are catching up time (classic fight with stopwatch) and then you have a duel with a single opponent.
From time to time, the police will also get involved, which further complicates all your efforts.
There are also passages outside the car.
Rather, it is just such interactive animations, when Jack usually flees from someone and you have to help him in this by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, though, these passages are far less in play than you might expect (perhaps even just three).
As a result, however, it is beneficial, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying and in the context of the above, it ranks among the elements that diversify the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous parts.
This means that it is definitely not a thing anymore, but it can not be said that it would be a negative.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-packed racing of this model is still quite good, even though we could find better ones in the competition.
So far, so good.
Problems begin to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer in order.
We do not expect this type of game to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea how your car will behave before hitting any object, then probably not everything is in order.
Typically, when overtaking or passing cars in normal traffic, sometimes you just lightly lick each other, but other times in almost identical situation your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even a straight shot.
Thanks to the system of reboots, it does not really matter, but it will detune you reliably.
Restarts are designed so that if you break down or go far off the track, the game will throw you back to the last clue on the track.
However, there are only five restarts available in each race.
When you run out of them, you have to start the race all over again.
This is more likely to help you if something goes wrong than if you rely on it.
Sometimes, however, even restarts do not help, only the need to learn the given section of the race by heart will solve them.
The big problem with the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some corners, for example, need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit into them.
Other times you will meet the "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or one minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you can see your opponent pass easily between two cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
It does not matter when you arrive, because it is “counted” so that the situation always occurs just before your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
Throughout the game you will come across several places where you, again regardless of time, always overtake the same opponent in the same place.
Most of all, it hits the end of the game on the long bridge, where you are going in the opposite direction.
The enemy must get there in front of you, no matter what the cost.
When he drives in front of you, it makes your overview of oncoming cars worse, so you probably spread there a couple of times.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and adrenaline, but the design is so obvious that it reliably quickly disgusts you.
And it's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, playing is fun and so much action in places that sometimes you can't quite keep track of what's flying.
And it doesn’t really matter whether it’s the concept with 50 unique tracks, shifting races so that boredom doesn’t have a chance or whatever.
An unusual idea is the exchange of cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas pumps on the roads, because that's where you can change the car, although in the vast majority of cases you can do with what you currently have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars on straight highways and exotic supercars for technical riding, for example on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand with the challenge mode, which are the races in the individual locations you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points to your profile, which is common to challenges and story.
Various items are unlocked to get a higher level of driver: from cars to profile backgrounds.
It is also linked to the online Autolog function, which, among other things, compares your achievements with other players and provides other community functions.
One of the other hard-to-understand kicks is the situation from the last race in the story.
Your car will take you to the subway tunnel (be), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (be).
The speedometer flashes the numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (be) and the subway comes from behind and crushes you uncompromisingly.
In the editorial office, we will probably have a few more days of discussion about whether nobody really thought a bit when creating the game, or whether the authors consider us really so big jerks.
The technical side of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in a few cases even great.
They get so frustrated that in some more tense moments the shooting decreases, and in some cases quite tragically.
But this is especially true for crashes with a larger number of participants, when smooth shooting would not be useful for you anyway.
The sound is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to the widest range of rather younger audiences, the soundtrack from the category "every dog different village" was created, but it can be assumed that because of listening to music, no one will buy the game.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so very self-conscious.
If the game avoided completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of NFS in the last few years.
But this is how the game works.
Fun is certainly fine, but be prepared for the fact that mistakes will hit you in the eye with the power of airport spotlights.
Singing choirs of Charles University will perform at the Velvet Students concert
The Festa Academica festival brings together the celebrations of the International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical experience for the third time.
During this time, he will introduce twenty high school and college choirs.
The main focus of the festival is two concerts held on 17 November.
"Charles University has a large share of the festival."
"Among the participating choirs is the Choir of the Faculty of Education and the Faculty of Humanities, the festival committee will be chaired by Rector Václav Hampl," said Jakub Čaloun, head of the organizing team.
The highlight of the festival is a free concert of high school choirs, which will take place on 17th November from 2 p.m. in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program includes a composition by the prominent Czech jazzman Karel Ruzicka Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, a concert "Salte students" will take place in the ceremonial premises of the National House in Vinohrady, where university choirs including choirs of Charles University will perform.
Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the International Student Day with dignity and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to develop creative cooperation among young people.
The main organizer is the Union of Czech Choirs in cooperation with the Jan Kepler Grammar School.
Bohuslav Svoboda, Mayor of Prague, and Václav Hampl, Rector of Charles University, took over the whole event.
The festival will take place from 16 to 20 November in Prague and Pardubice.
In addition to the gala concerts, the schedule also offers a variety of music meetings, student happenings, matinees and other shows.
Detailed information can be found on the festival website www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador to the EU Vice-President:
Czechs have a reputation for being negative and Eurosceptic
"The Lisbon Treaty has significantly upset the balance between the various institutions."
"I didn't expect it to be such a tough war."
"It will take five or six years for the situation to settle down a bit and for all players to get used to their new roles," Czech Ambassador to the European Union Milena Vicenová said.
Insofar as she takes her motto "Comprehensively and openly about Europe" seriously, she showed in the first part of the lecture that she managed to describe the individual EU institutions and their relations in such a clear and understandable way that many lecturers from the Faculty of Law of Charles University might envy her.
