It also wants to make better use of the EU environment and get more Czechs into European institutions.
We have a multi-speed Europe.
According to the ambassador, the Czechs have a reputation as Eurosceptics and people who notice the negative rather than positive aspects of the matter.
Moreover, she regrets the low representation of Czechs in European institutions.
According to her, many factors are to blame, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational letters, but also low support from the Czech side.
In addition to the successful Czech Presidency, it highlighted the strength and cooperation of the Visegrad Four.
"Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come up to me and a Slovak comes up, the Frenchman next to me says, 'Hey, what's going on there, what's your Visegrad Four doing?' and he doesn't look excited about it at all."
In the future, the EU will face tough new rules on member states’ budgetary policies.
He sees as very real the concept of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe, rather than a new "European Federation."
“We have eurozone countries and countries outside the eurozone.”
"We have the Schengen area, we already have the institution of enhanced cooperation."
"For the first time, it was said that only the countries that want to cooperate and those that don't want to stay away."
“There will be more institutes and it will be a strong two-speed Europe,” she said.
In this regard, it also appreciated the role of the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the principle that all issues affecting the whole Union should be discussed between all Member States, not only between the euro area countries.
Brand story:
IBM innovator begins the second century of its existence
If someone were to search for a word that most accurately conveys IBM's strategy, the closest would probably be "long-term".
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is perceived as very contemporary, and yet a hundred years have passed since its founding.
The foundation of this long-term business was laid by the company’s first boss, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the slogan that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His slogan "Think!" became the imprint around which the life of the future giant will unfold (and also the name of the internal magazine, which began to be published at IBM in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson’s carefully built corporate culture.
“For us at IBM, long-term thinking means a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a century because it remained true to its core values while not being afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society during our first century.
We hope to achieve even more in the second hundred,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current CEO.
Sophisticated system
In the 1930s, Watson took a similar approach to caring for his employees as Bata in the Czech Republic - people from IBM were among the first American employees to have paid holidays, insurance from an employer, plus an elegant employee uniform and an elaborate system for rewarding the best inventors and businessmen.
IBM has a long-standing relationship with its customers.
From the beginning, the company was brilliant at extracting talent - as one of the world's first companies, it abolished any discrimination, so it could choose.
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy, the current plan is for Palmisan to be replaced next year by a woman named Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for 30 years and is still the head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has been doing so-called pits, online brainstorming, from which arise many future strategies and innovations.
