IBM History: From Cheese Slicer to Space Flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a century ago, originally with the complex name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The IBM name was adopted in 1924 and was originally used for the company's offices in Canada and South America.
The merger of four companies dates back to the 1880s.
They owned technologies such as the famous "crackles," that is, clocks recording the employee's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new firm was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the firm's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired rival firm head Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of IBM - Watson's ideas are still built on invincible corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production and sale of all kinds of machines for business - from meat and cheese slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson’s leadership, the company doubled its turnover to $9 million and began a large-scale expansion to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that his son, Thomas Watson Junior, succeeded him after nearly forty years in the boss’s chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA fly into space - to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the famous manned flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "care" that set the computer standard at the time, called the IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer manufacturing to Chinese company Lenovo, bought consulting arm PricewaterhouseCoopers, and became fully engaged in consulting and high-value-added services.
The strategy that has paid off over the past three years is the concept of a Smarter Planet.
Its aim is the smart use of technologies in previously unplanned areas and the improvement of the situation, for example, in transport or city administration.
For business, IBM recently introduced a "Smarter Commerce" platform that helps merchants manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history at home.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932 as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM Czech Republic, it also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and there is also a world-class research team dealing with voice recognition.
