How prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time were selling mostly only tours to socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled to the GDR (Democratic Republic of Germany), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea by the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when the possibility to travel to Yugoslavia was also, however, then the Yugoslav regime inclined towards the West and the travels of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the travel agency.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without the foreign exchange pledge it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) to travel to the West.
However, by far the most frequent holidays were spent in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages, which the Czechs acquired and this custom survives to this day.
Czechs have experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of, is that it was not possible for us to travel to the most popular Croatia until 1989, as it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa requirements for neighboring Western European countries were lifted, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits, mainly to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there at least for a while.
In Paris, for example, tours of Czechs slept in tents in parks, as our income at that time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czech travel at this time was bringing your own food, canned food, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech koruna, which allowed our tourists to finally buy Western currency after many decades.
However, our standard of living and, with it, average salaries rose, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Due to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to regularly prepare charter flights since 1997, which has made air tours incredibly cheaper compared to the past thanks to the possibility of arranging quantity discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs had already had visa-free access to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which continued to facilitate our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to Thailand was dispatched from the Czech Republic due to considerable demand.
Since this year, Czech tourists have been flying direct charters to warm faraway countries every year, this winter they will fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. canceled visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time ever, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3%), and for the first time in history, they spent more than CZK 15,000 per person on one foreign vacation, including the cost of staying there.
