Intelligent crows are spreading in cities
In many places, field ravens are considered "problem birds": however, these highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven out of cities, experts say.
Some like them, others would like to get rid of them quite quickly: Crows have been part of the image of the city for centuries, yet in some municipalities there are complaints of pollution and noise caused by animals.
However, there is no such thing as "problem birds" yet.
Field ravens may no longer be driven out of cities, experts said at the first symposium on crows in Leer, East Africa.
There, experts from all over the federal territory discussed possible starting points.
They are looking for alternatives in cities.
Conservationists also derived urban problems from the exodus of specially protected field ravens: The use of chemistry in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional areas for life.
Persecution, growing and felling of typical trees for nesting birds make life difficult.
Crows are protected.
Large colonies with more than 600 nesting pairs are found in Soest, Westphalia, in the northwest, in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and in Leer, among others.
There, the 2005 disputed project of mass killings of crows in the rural district generated negative headlines.
Critics have described trapping animals for birds and beating sticks as particularly brutal.
"Normal banishment, alarm, does not bring anything", so much found the urbanist and landscaper Werner Kluever of Leer.
Removing nests by spraying water or felling trees often has undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser of Lahr in Baden-Wuerttemberg.
"Animals retreat, large colonies cleave and divide into other places".
Scaring is only conceivable as an exception in hospitals, retirement homes, or schools.
"We have to live with them, we can't get them out."
Without the surrounding territory, the problem of cities cannot be solved, was the opinion of Mayor Wolfgang Kellner of Leer.
A combination of expelling animals from sensitive residential areas and luring them to settle in other places is conceivable.
"Information board instead of chainsaws" was promoted by psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jurgens for a completely different treatment of animals: "One shilling in the face we can best overcome with self-confidence."
In Schleswig-Holstein, Mrs. Jurgens co-founded the Ascherberg Educational Crow Trail, which provides information boards on the life of the highly intelligent field raven.
The project has since been accepted by tourists.
Also, on the criticism of the noise caused by birds, Mrs. Jurgens had her own opinion: "Here it is about every volume of communication, they have much to say to each other."
The intelligence and skill of animals are legendary: The field ravens not only use tools to reach the treat, but even make their own tools.
Researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested the behavior on four field ravens as far as the intelligence of birds reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to bring the stones down to get to the moth’s larva.
Without much training, they knew what size and shape the stone must have to cause the platform to collapse.
In the second attempt, the cunning crows then had to solve a more difficult problem.
In the vertical cylinders, the researchers placed a small container with a moth larva.
Birds could not reach their prey with their beaks.
But the researchers put pieces of wire in there.
From them all four animals formed a hook, with which she used as a hook to hunt from the tube a container by the handle.
Three of the four field ravens even managed to do so with a hitch.
