Massacre on a personal level
Peter Englund’s emotionally powerful new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War, begins with a list of characters that will make your head spin.
One piece of advice to follow in that moment: Carefully tear out this page and make it a bookmark.
You will get to know all the people very well in Mr. Englund’s novel narrative, and this list will serve as a navigation - as a kind of beacon - at times when you, like the men and women in the story, will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as "anti-historical work".
It contains several well-known names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and discussions about tactics and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, but rather a "book about what it was like". It mainly deals with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and Grief" combines the war experiences of 20 more-or-less-dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from female students and botanists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers, and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flicker like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the tangle of fates while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is different from classic historical novels.
It reinterprets the notion that World War I was just about the horrific trench battles on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Grief" skillfully explores other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve the problems of falling bee nests, having to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids or struggling with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, it was a very touching read.
War consumes people's lives like some natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When gunfire starts in the distance and you're the woman who's home with your kids, do you run or stay?
Who's coming?
Hardly anyone understands what is going on, not even why the whole war has been unleashed.
"The vacuum arising from lack of facts," observed Mr. Englund, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Grief" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from CVs, letters and other published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound scary and engaging, but with the inclusion of small moments and details, they are completely vivid and believable.
Many of them talk about suffering and coping with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Substitutes, substitutes everywhere."
"Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It mentions "meat made from pressed rice cooked in mutton fat (and supplemented with a false bone made of wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, boots with wooden soles".
He mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the making of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds in himself an interior impulse to savagery and brutality, whereupon he declares of war: "In the end, you will understand that this is human nature. Not to sit in comfortable armchairs with a cigarette and whiskey, an evening newspaper or a good book, pretending that this mask of yours represents civilization and that behind the starched self there is no barbarian hidden inside."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
"When one finally accepts sacrifice, one would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience," she writes.
Instead, he feels like a "convicted man who is secretly hanged".
Other remarks concern the departure of old Europe and the emergence of new horrors.
“Conflict has increasingly become economic competition and competitive struggle,” writes Mr. Englund, “war between factories.”
