Walls Have Eyes: How Scientists Are Researching You on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to the July killing rampage that left 77 dead in Norway, attended his first public hearing.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he was certainly not alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time at the computer during the preparation of the attack, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just go to Facebook.
“We realized getting them isn’t really that hard at all,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently released report by a British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so vast, Bartlett says, that scientists simply needed to use site advertising to pinpoint the demographics they were looking for, something that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe, and they drew attention to them and sent them advertisements. However, instead of inviting them into the newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire asking questions about their level of education, their relationship to violence, and their optimism about their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a completely new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are irritated by the rising rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more sensible, more democratic, and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind a computer screen.”
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists, and political researchers use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends, including status updates, wall posts, and “I like” buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. On average, each of them provides three different data per day, which makes this social network literally a "information supernova", which is responsible for the development of many new research. The number of academic works in which the word Facebook appears has increased from five years ago to almost 800%.
For some scientists, the magic of Facebook is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to do a survey of people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to go to a party where they'd never let you," Bartlett says.
"This is all degraded by Facebook - you just go right to them."
Others argue that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a socio-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, a research team found that university students who discussed their drunken ascents on Facebook were far more at risk for the problem of alcoholism than students who were silent about the topic.
Moreno suggests that peers monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who posts too many drunken statuses.
“The problem can’t be solved if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior, and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
"We've found a way to identify at-risk children that we wouldn't otherwise have had a chance to discover."
Facebook constantly probes its users’ data.
The site’s information team has produced statistics related to the relationship statuses and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in 2010 and the nation’s satisfaction rate (mainly using the information they had access to - proponents of internet freedom have long argued that the site should make its information treasure available for others to research).
But Facebook users know that the site is following them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the site.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don’t even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most users even thought that scientists could look at their profiles," said Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study he conducted using his students' public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it as if the information was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even when researched offline, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much of your profile information and wall posts are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn explains.
That’s why Selwin, who has spent years researching new technologies, thinks that the pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool to use in research.
“When you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it’s something that can’t be replaced,” he says.
"Social research should be about society and social activities - and a hell of a lot of social activities are still taking place off-line."
