"I am a military commander in the Norwegian resistance movement and among the Norwegian Knights Templar," he told the court, where 500 people gathered.
"I object to the Court of Justice because you have been mandated by organizations that support an ideology of hate and because it promotes multiculturalism."
"I confess my actions, but I admit no guilt for them."
Judge Torkjel Nesheim interrupted Breivik during the monologue because he "didn't want to give Breivik the opportunity to use this hearing as a platform from which to voice his views."
For the same reason, he refused to allow Breivik, who had brought a prepared speech with him, to address the relatives of his victims at the end of the hearing.
Nesheim also ordered police to keep Breivik in custody for another 12 weeks, banned him from any media contact for 4 weeks, and announced that the authorities would have full control over all his visits and all correspondence for eight weeks.
About 30 relatives of the victims and survivors attended the hearing.
Some came in the hope of being able to look Breivik in the eye, others to make sure he was kept firmly under lock and key.
They all participated in order to move the case to early closure.
"It seemed to me that he looked cold and inhuman," one of the survivors of the attack told an NRK commentator.
"It wasn't pleasant, but I can tell you that after seeing and hearing the suspect, I mentally moved a little further."
Breivik, dressed in a dark suit and blue tie, remained calm and professional throughout the hearing, with no trouble looking journalists and survivors in the eye on their arrival and departure.
Despite Breivik's bizarre notion that he was part of a larger "resistance" movement, the judge noted that there was no evidence that he had any accomplices.
Some may find it comforting that the June 22 attacks appear to be the work of a single extremist, not a group of radicals.
However, this does not automatically diminish the grief and confusion that are still in the minds and hearts of the entire nation.
"I wish she looked like a monster, but she doesn't," said a relative of one of the victims.
“If it were, things would be a lot easier.”
7 lessons from a lost interview with Steve Jobs in a movie this week
When Steve Jobs died on October 5, the opinions of people who compared him to Henry Ford - and elected him as his genius The Greatest Modern Inventor.
In a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs, which was dusted off for a special movie this week, Apple fans will be amazed that his creative mind has completely understood the business processes and workflows behind his products.
He was an amazing designer, a dreamer and a self-proclaimed member of the hippie movement, but also a pedantic organizer and a person who fine-tunes every little detail - believing that many entrepreneurs suffer from "the idea that a really great idea is 90 percent of their job... [but] there's still a long way to go between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was working on a TV show called "The Triumph of the Computer Fools," which dealt with the dawn of personal computers.
By then, it had been ten years since Jobs was forced to leave Apple, and he was busy with his new computer company, NeXT, and eagerly watched the general public adopt the Internet.
In the end, only a short portion of the entire Cringely interview was used on the TV show, and the original copies of the interview were rumored to have been lost in transit.
Shortly after Jobs' death, however, VHS copies were found in the director's garage.
It is this material, slightly edited, that forms the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is heading to selected cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is famous for his reluctance to give longer interviews, Jobs is surprisingly excited to talk about his technology philosophy and business strategies.
He also appears to be a very thoughtful man.
Four times during the interview, a longer pause occurs between the question and the answer - 10 to 15 seconds of thinking, when you can see how Jobs perfectly thinks the answer to be as concise and accurate as possible.
There are also moments when Jobs’s perfectionism comes to the surface, when he is impatient with Cringely’s questions and drives him to get to more important issues and topics faster.
The interview was filmed before the Pixar, iPod, or iPhone era, and features frighteningly prophetic thoughts as Jobs assesses what other companies are doing well and wrong while offering his own vision of the future in the field of computer technology.
It’s one thing to read through the posthumous ratings of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about Jobs, who we see here as an eager dreamer in the heyday of his genius.
It has its own vision of what things could and should look like.
It wasn’t long before he started putting his ideas into practice.
A quick summary of seven scenes from The Lost Interview that are definitely worth noting:
How he learned to run a business:
"Throughout the years of business, I've always asked, 'Why are you doing this?' and the answer has always been the same: 'Well, that's just how it's done.'"
No one knows why he does what he does, he never thinks deeply about business-related things.
That's what I found out.
Jobs continues by describing his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
He was completely confused by the way costs were recorded - they often started with the words "standard costs", he could only guess at their amount. At that point, he decided to go his own way - he developed an automatic tool that guaranteed that they could determine the business costs in a moment.
How he ransacked the Pope:
Jobs recalls the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into a phone company and make free calls anywhere in the world.
A lot has been written about the device in the past, but Jobs’ enthusiasm at describing the Blue Box as an instrument of power is literally contagious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the device using a paid phone and allowed themselves to be switched from one AT&T network to another while using as many satellites as possible.
“We’ve been around the world at least half a dozen times, so when we yelled something into a pay phone, it was called a minute later from the second phone at the door,” Jobs laughs.
“We were young, and we found that we could build a thing that could manage billions of dollars of infrastructure all over the world.”
The two of us made a tiny little thing that was able to control a much bigger giant - it was an incredible experience and I don't think Apple would have been created without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a prank he and Wozniak nearly pulled to completion. Through the Blue Box in the middle of the night, they called the Vatican asking if they could talk to the Pope, impersonating Henry Kissinger as best they could.
Gradually, increasingly senior members of the Catholic Church were called in to talk to an American diplomat in the middle of the night, and it was only just before the Pope himself was awakened that the pair fluttered and put the earpiece down.
How he fell in love with technology (and phoned Bill Hewlett):
When he was 12 and was looking for spare parts to build a oscillator, he found Bill Hewlett's phone number in the phone book and called him.
Not long after their 20-minute interview, Jobs had already secured a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It influenced me incredibly. It was the only company I knew at the time, and it shaped my view of what a company really is and how it should treat its employees."
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a CRT monitor, and I fell in love with it immediately.
As a teenager at HP, I progressed higher and higher, I hung around that computer and started writing programs for it.
How to invent innovation:
In several places, Jobs talks about how he invents new products on the fly.
Early in his career, when he set out to sell a few printed circuit boards, one customer asked him to assemble an entire computer for him.
He had only 30 paid days, during which he had to invent, assemble and deliver the finished equipment.
When he was later at Apple, he recalls the problems they faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember we were fighting pretty fiercely... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to assemble a mouse that would cost $300] until I got tired of it, I went out and found a designer."
Ninety days later, we were able to make a perfectly reliable mouse for $15.
How Big Companies Are Breathing:
Long before he led Apple’s resurrection, Jobs foresightedly predicted that many industry leaders would falter in their vision and lose their market share.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers or printers, so what’s next?”
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company can no longer be more successful.
At that point, sales and marketing are in control, so companies are led by people who are in charge of this, while people who are in charge of their own products are out of the decision-making process.
The technological genius who has led the company to its unshakable position is now replaced by people who have no idea of good or bad products - skill and technical knowledge are necessary.
This is exactly what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could literally own the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times bigger than it was, it could have been Microsoft in the nineties...
Instead of winning, they lost.
How he views innovation as an art form:
“There’s still a long way to go between a great idea and a great product...and as the great idea evolves, it changes and grows.”
During that time, you will learn a lot about it.
You have to make a number of compromises - certain things you just can't make electrons, glass, robots or factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in mind all the time - different concepts - and put them together...
In the end, taste matters - you try to think of the best things that humanity has ever created, and in some way you try to project them into what you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, but the best artists steal.
I've never been ashamed to steal the best ideas.
The Macintosh was so amazing and successful because the people who worked at it were excellent musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, and coincidentally also the best computer experts in the world.
Without computers and new technologies, they would be able to do amazing things in completely different industries.
Scalia and Thomas dined with opponents of the Health Care Act while their case was being handled by the court.
On the day the Supreme Court sat behind closed doors to discuss the politically controversial issue of whether to accept an objection to President Obama's health care bill, two of its judges, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, attended a gala dinner sponsored by a law firm that will attend the hearing in front of the court.
The incident occurred last Thursday when all nine judges met to discuss the motions tabled.
One of the cases under consideration was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging a radical overhaul of health care passed last year by Congress - a bill that mobilized conservative activists around the world.
The judges have agreed to hear the case, but a 5.5-hour hearing is expected in March, with the result further galvanizing presidential elections scheduled for 2012 and in full swing at the time of the ruling.
The lawyer who will stand up in court and try to get the bill rejected will most likely be Paul Clement, who served as Attorney General of the United States under George W. Bush.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society group, which has been engaged in advocacy for conservative legal principles for many years.
Another company that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations challenging the law, the so-called National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, for which huge funds are at stake.
The dinner was held in a Washington hotel a few hours after a court discussion on the subject of the case.
It was attended by, among others, Mitch McConnell, the highest representative of Republicans in the Senate and a confirmed opponent of the Health Care Act.
Scalia and Thomas.
This is nothing new: This pair of judges has been participating in the Federalist Society for years.
There is nothing that goes against the rules of ethics.
In fact, these judges are exempt from complying with the principles of conduct to which lower federal judges are subject.
If it were not, however, their conduct would certainly fall under the C4 principle, which states that "a judge may participate in events that are currently being held by related and other organizations for the purpose of obtaining funding, but a judge may not be a speaker, an honorary guest, nor be featured on the agenda of the event."
Still, Scalia and Thomas’ relationship to the two law firms involved in the case, as well as to a company with a huge financial stake in the case, was enough to alert activists calling for ethics in the government.
"This shocking breach of ethics and indifference to the code of conduct contradicts the assertion by several judges that the Supreme Court is behaving according to the same rules that apply to all other federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"Judges drank and dined at a community fundraiser along with attorneys waiting to hear their case in court."
Their presence and assistance in raising funds through this action undermines the feet of all claims of disinterestedness, which is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas showed little sympathy for their critics, telling them that they also seamlessly combined their judicial duties with the actions of groups such as the Federalist Society.
Thomas's wife Ginni is a high-profile conservative activist.
In addition, conservatives argue that the ethical problem lies mainly with Judge Elena Kagan and not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan served as Attorney General under President Obama when the first objections to the law appeared before the court.
Kagan's critics are pressuring her to relinquish her involvement in the case, claiming that she fought for the law so much back then that she could now be disinterested.
Kagan had no indication that she was about to resign.
Boeing wins record $18 billion jet contract
Emirates Airlines is ordering 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle jets with the option to purchase 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Aman Air for more than $1 billion.
When a company gets an order for 50 of its products, it’s usually no reason to celebrate.
However, if the company is a Boeing Co. aircraft manufacturer and the cost of these 50 aircraft totals a record $18 billion, it is something else.
Equally important is where Boeing got the order from: the Middle East, a sprawling gold mine for future aircraft orders.
