On Monday, Boeing announced that Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, sometimes called Dreamliners, with significantly improved fuel economy and passenger facilities.
The total cost of these six aircraft exceeds $1 billion.
“This is excellent news for Boeing,” said Neal Dihora, an analyst at Morningstar.
"The quality of these specific customers is very high."
Many of the airlines in the Middle East belong to the oil-producing nations.
This means that not only do they have money to pay for planes, but the rise in the price of fuel - mostly damaging to the airline because it is one of its biggest costs - is not so decisive, because the country itself makes money from higher oil prices.
This is important because they are not as likely as other airlines to cancel or delay aircraft orders due to fuel price increases, Dihora said.
“It’s a natural protection,” he said.
The order from Emirates reinforces Boeaing’s leading position in the wide-body aircraft market and brings Airbus SAS to the fore in an attempt to undermine Boeing’s dominance with its A350 transport model.
Boeing's victory comes four months after representatives from Airbus announced the postponement of the first flight of their largest A350 aircraft, which is a direct competitor to the 777-300ER.
The displacement occurred because customers demanded more payload and range, so the manufacturer took the time to deliver more engine power to the machine.
The price of Boeing Co shares rose 1.5% to $67.94.
