ADB urges Asia to help save eurozone
The Asian Development Bank called on India and China to be prepared to help save the eurozone from its severe debt crisis, otherwise the global economy could suffer a global downturn, which would also have a negative impact on the growth of economies in Asia.
Rajat Nag, chief executive of Manila-based ADB, said the world's two fastest-growing economies must "do everything in their power" to help the currency bloc recover rapidly through the International Monetary Fund, or through direct bilateral agreements.
He warned that the countries of the Bric Group [Brazil, Russia, India, China] are watching all European troubles “too unexcitingly” and said that Asian financial aid, combined with European leadership and funds, would help ward off the long-term collapse of the global economy.
"We're all in this together."
“So anyone who could help Europe out of the crisis is a good fit,” he told the Financial Times during an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
“Asia may be protected to some extent, but it’s certainly not immune.”
“So if China and India can help, they definitely should.”
The European Monetary Association has been suffering from a severe debt crisis for several months.
In recent days, Italy’s borrowing costs have risen dangerously, and the prime ministers of both Italy and Greece have resigned.
The growing debt crisis in Europe raised fears that it could bring the global economy back into recession, and calls began to emerge to bring the newly booming leading economies together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that all Asian support would be channelled through the IMF, but noted that bilateral aid - such as the purchase of bonds by the European Union's Financial Assistance Fund, the European Financial Stability Facility - would provide greater bargaining opportunities for Asian partners of European countries.
Anand Sharma, India's trade minister, said that "India will do its best" to help the eurozone, as its own economy now suffers from a decline in exports and a drying up of foreign capital inflows.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and restless," he said.
"We are facing a difficult task and we must maintain a high rate of growth."
"It's not an alternative, it's a bare fact, because how else could we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women."
Others argue that emerging economies, such as India, have nothing to do to help European economies when they are forced to face their own serious economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the U.S., said it would be politically very difficult to explain aid to Europe's 1.2 billion inhabitants of India, with 800 million of them living on $2 or less a day.
“One day they might find out that the Greeks are retiring at 50 and enjoying their holidays on the beaches, which would probably be difficult to explain,” he said.
Lee Howell, director general of the World Economic Forum, similarly questioned why Indian supplies should be used to keep well-paid jobs for many Greek citizens in poorly managed and loss-making sectors such as rail transport.
Mr Nag stressed that the eurozone crisis was threatening a "dangerous domino effect".
The bank’s forecast of 7.5% economic growth in Asia between 2011 and 2012 now faces a “risk of decline” due to the European threat.
He said vulnerable emerging markets must develop “plans of unforeseeable spending” to protect them from falling and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Pentagon Warning of Possible Defense Cuts
Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta put a lot of pressure on Congress on Monday when he warned that looming automatic budget cuts could threaten national security and trigger a financial chain reaction starting at the Pentagon and continuing through the battlefields of Afghanistan to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon will already have to spend $450 billion in budget cuts over the next decade, but it is now worried about a further $600 billion cut if Congress fails to reach a spending deal.
"The effects of these cuts would be devastating for the entire resort," Panetta wrote in a letter to Senators John McCain, Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, South Carolina.
He said that Congress' failure to reach a budget agreement and the resulting so-called attachment will cause a 23% flat-rate decline and halt many new projects.
"Because of such a huge reduction, used in this indiscriminate way, it will not be possible to carry out most of our construction or shipbuilding projects - you can't just buy three-quarters of a building or a ship. Moreover, it could seriously damage other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to senators.
"We will also be forced to separate many of our civilian employees, and since the reduction is to take place so quickly, we will also almost certainly have to send civilians on forced leave in order to be able to meet the target requirements."
"These changes may shake the faith of those who care about our military and seriously damage its preparedness."
In the end, the cuts will also affect combat units, Panetta announced.
"Although the accounts for the financing of possible war operations overseas will not be directly affected by this stoppage, the operations there will be negatively affected by major changes in other budgets," Panetta warned.
"There will also be cuts in contract staff, which will result in a delay in the contracted contracts supporting the war effort of our people."
"The payroll of employees will be reduced, which will result in late payments to suppliers and the consequent disruption of legal and political support."
The two senators wrote to Panetta 10 days ago asking him for details about the possible impact on automatic cuts in the Department of Defense.
"The consequences of a stoppage in the Department of Defense could cause a rapid degradation of the view of the United States as a world military power."
"We are strictly against this harsh measure," the senators announced in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
"It's not a conclusion we can live with, and we certainly don't want to sign up for it."
"Planned cuts are a threat to the national security of the United States, which we should not allow."
"It remains to be seen whether Panetta's letter and fresh warnings will increase pressure on Congress approving the budget and amplify calls to remove the Pentagon from the list of cut-off areas.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken in recent talks about possible cuts, even as he transitioned to his senior position at the Pentagon with years of Congressional and White House budget approval experience, so he knew he was getting into a tough fight.
At a press conference held last week, the defence minister gave a brief picture of what his department might expect - the shell of the military, but inside it will be missing a core.
"He'll be like a ship without sailors."
"He'll be like a brigade without ammo."
"It will be like an air force without trained pilots."
"He'll be like a paper tiger, like an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to complete the mission," Panetta said at the start of a speech at the Pentagon.
"She will be like a moraleless unit, unprepared and unable to cope with a possible enemy."
"As a result, he will welcome aggression..."
In an attachment delivered with a letter to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifies how the reduction will result in "significant operational risks: late response to crises, conflicts, and disasters; significant reduction in dropout and deployment options worldwide; anticipated unacceptable risk in future combat operations."
Panetta added that some of the biggest defense projects could be expected to end, including those already being tested and those still in the early stages of planning.
The list included the F35 project, a planned new bomber, a next-generation ballistic submarine, a new coastal battleship, and a new ground combat vehicle to replace the Humvee.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 would save $80 billion over the next decade, but its proponents say this is a necessary next step in improving the military needed to deal with possible threats from China and other rivals.
How to recognize a lie
A glance at recent newspaper headlines shows just how serious and pervasive lies and deceptions are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain has his hands full accusing him of sexually harassing several women, both sides claiming the other is lying.
Administrators at Penn State University were charged with perjury when they tried to hide records of a retired football coach sexually assaulting a boy.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught telling US President Barack Obama with a microphone that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has been able to destroy entire careers and cloud the stability of many countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself when he published information that was immediately refuted by indisputable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of abusing his campaign funds to try to conceal his extramarital affair.
And no one will ever forget the media circus surrounding Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term in office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
There are stories of cheating at school and university.
There are cases where teachers give their students test answers just to make themselves look good in their assessments.
Mentors, who should teach the opposite, send the message that lies and deception are acceptable.
How many scams do we encounter?
Studies show that you lie somewhere between 10 and 200 times in a single day.
Let us suppose that many of them are merciful lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times during the first ten minutes of their first encounter.
Identifying lies, or “recognition of lies,” is a necessary skill that should be learned by everyone, whether for personal or professional reasons.
However, it is not a social game that is similar to, say, Charade, where one shouts, "I have you." Deception is a serious branch of science working with scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities in the course of detailed research projects, especially in the field of psychology and philosophy.
One of the results of the research is that most of the old myths about lies have been refuted.
Liars look you in the eye.
It's not like they're stuttering, stuttering, blushing, or stitching.
However, do not assume that it is difficult to spot and detect liars.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from a sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I’ve spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a large and growing sector of lie-recognition, and it’s clear that exposing deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and can help you a lot in today’s complex world, especially if your job responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them relax their guard, direct their emotions, and intuitively recognize how the other party accepts them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "focused on others" - mostly to protect one's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (but the lies they tell are usually "outrageous").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of the subject.
This is called "initial observation."
It will give you something to compare it to later.
Note the posture of the subject, his laughter, work with the voice.
You should know if someone is patting their feet all the time, so you don’t wrongfully accuse them of lying just because they start patting their foot in the middle of the meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
Think of it as a warning sign, not a lie.
Lying people may stop moving the top half of their body as they try to remember their made-up story, turn their toes to the door, lean toward the exit, significantly change posture, or show "relief after the conversation" - over-relaxing relaxation and changing position when confession is difficult behind them.
Interviewers often give a false signal that the interview is over, just to see what the relief will look like when it is over.
See the subject’s language.
Famous is the story of how Scott Peterson once misspoke and used the past tense when he claimed his murdered wife was alive, triggering a nationwide search for her body.
Lying individuals may also express themselves aloofly: "I had no sexual relationship with that lady... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat the difficult question.
The most common verbal signs are very slight.
Someone can use a lot of "melting language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... from what I know... to the best of my knowledge."
In such an answer, we do not learn too many facts, and often this is another warning sign.
There is no magic that can detect every lie, but it is possible to acquire the skills to detect it.
Using these skills, you will have a better chance of not falling for a liar and a fraud in your personal and professional life.
Controversial plan to build oil pipeline will be rerouted after threat of delaying US government approval
A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned oil pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico - pitting trade unions against each other but placating environmentalists - the pipeline construction company announced it was willing to redirect the project to get things moving again.
TransCanada announced on Monday evening that it will move the planned pipeline route from the environmentally sensitive Sandhills area of Nebraska, and is confident that the project will be approved anyway.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Nebraska government headquarters.
TransCanada’s Alex Pourbax says the company believes the pipeline will eventually be approved, even though it will run a different route.
The announcement came after the State Department said last week it was delaying a decision to federally authorize the project, from where it would not conduct studies of possible alternate routes through which it could not intervene in the Sandhills area of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a sprawling underground water reservoir.
"This is really a move forward," Republican Rep. Lee Terry of Nebraska told Fox News.
A new environmental assessment ordered by the Foreign Ministry would probably postpone any decision until 2013, one year after next year’s election, but the authorities deny that politics played a role in the decision.
In a written statement last week, Obama described the decision as a State Department request and expressed his support for it.
The 1,700-mile pipeline will connect Canada and the Gulf of Mexico.
From the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas, it flows 700,000 barrels of oil every day.
Six states will have to cross this path.
This project is absolutely hated by environmentalists, but loved by work crews, who estimate that 20,000 new jobs will be created while working on the pipeline.
However, Nebraska lawmakers opposed the plan and considered introducing laws that would force the company not to intervene in the Sand Hills region and the Ogallala aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
An existing environmental impact study commissioned by the State Department found that the project would only have a minor negative environmental impact, but a source from the energy industry said the Department Inspector General ordered a new review of the entire process of the original study, focusing mainly on two issues.
