Patti LaBelle is accused of making a toddler throw up.
The New York family says singer Patti LaBelle stormed into the lobby of their Manhattan home and scared their daughter into throwing up.
"Lady Marmalade's performance scared 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disorder" and "increased fear of strangers," her family said in a lawsuit filed with Manhattan's Supreme Court.
On November 10 last year, stage technician Kevin Monk, his wife Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were going on a family trip.
When Kevin Monk pulled up the car, Roseanna Monk came down to the lobby of their house on Riverside Boulevard and carried Genevieve with her.
Roseanna Monk said she stopped at the door for a moment and put the baby away for a moment.
"Someone showed up behind my back and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing?' I said 'yes' and I left to pick her up"
LaBelle irritably reprimanded the pregnant woman.
"She said to me in an aggressive tone, 'You shouldn't put your daughter at the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
"I told her, 'I don't care about your opinion.'"
She got angry and began to speak dirty - she screamed out the meanest expressions...
She had a bottle of water on her, and she started splashing water all over me.
She claims Genevieve had a hysterical seizure.
"I said to the woman, 'Look what you did to my daughter,'" the mother said.
LaBelle threw herself at her mother - who was still in Genevieve's arms - and had to be stopped by her escort, who then dragged her to the waiting car, Roseanna Monk testified.
The little girl screamed so much that she threw up, she added.
Later, the family sent a letter demanding an apology from LaBelle, but received no response.
LaBelle’s lawyer and spokesperson have not responded to our calls to comment on the case.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, but the family's attorney, Sam Davis, said he took the case for free and that the family plans to donate all of the money to a charity dedicated to children with cancer.
"The purpose is to force Patti LaBelle to accept responsibility for her actions," Davis said.
"This behavior is totally unacceptable, especially when it's directed at a school teacher holding an 18-month-old child."
Disadvantages of the climate have hampered the economy.
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's rule, unemployment and unreliability rose in Sinaloa, foreign investment declined, and with it the economy
The year 2011 will go down in the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the reign of Mario López Valdez, who calls himself the government of change. This government has brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to the adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, no growth has been recorded and even the main indicators of economic development have declined.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the possibilities of growth of the state economy, and caused a 3.6% decrease in economic activity in the first semester of this year. In the field of agriculture, there was a historical decrease of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78.03% was completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07% was found to be partially damaged. The main crops destroyed include vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity until November was caused by a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state saw an increase during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 Sinaloa residents were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% against the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment rose to about 5,28%, and between July and August, the average unemployment rate rose further, reaching 6.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on the steps taken at the level of public policy.
"We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors. These include, among other things, loss of liquidity in the market due to resource constraints due to legislation passed by Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn them, invest them or use them for something," he stressed.
Stop the migration
López Cervantes said that demographic factors also contributed to the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both because of the difficulty of entering and because even if these people cross the border, it is difficult for them to get a job. So people stay and demand work from our state, and so unemployment is rising," he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the increasing unreliability that prevails in the field of working conditions. According to the National Institute of Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of employed people in the state work without paying benefits to the Social Security Administration.
To unemployment and unreliability are added other features of the labor market, such as low salaries. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries from the whole country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was 5,352 pesetas by September, well below the national average of 7,375 pesetas.
Shortening of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, there was also the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697 between January and June, a decrease of 87.74% compared to $5,143,312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the government of the state reports investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year. These investments were mainly directed to service businesses.
Debt
In connection with the economic downturn scenario, the government of this state asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso. This would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million peso. Until November, no debt gains were recorded, in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés pointed out the lack of management skills of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the National Chamber of Transformational Industries, said there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the state government itself, in 2011.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa has been really minuscule during this year. We have to work hard to regain the land we lost this year. In 2012, we have to redouble the effort, there was no harmonization of the efforts of all of us and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo López said events such as the frost at the beginning of the year had halted the state's economy and limited its development and growth.
"The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore dynamism, which would allow to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. Therefore, at the end of the year, we found ourselves far below the expected forecasts," he said.
Redefining the Mission
According to Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Employer’s Confederation of the Republic of Mexico in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed into more dynamic productive activities.
"Generally speaking, we observe that work is being done. We believe that it is necessary to prepare a long-term plan in which the goals and economic direction of the state would be redefined, because it is important that all the potential of material and human resources that Sinaloa has is mobilized," he said.
The work ahead of us
President Coparmex stressed the importance of setting out a vision for the future that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there have been some progress in the area of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term plan," he said.
He stated that the current administration has shown progress in terms of public policy leadership.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that there is work done here and I think the government is aware that there is a lot of work ahead of us too," he said.
