He stated that last year under the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padilla, the state did not meet the relevant supplies, and therefore at the beginning of the new period, the city had to apply for a loan in order to be able to pay more than 7 million, which was not given to them by the state administration.
"The same thing happened to us already in the previous six-year period, because the state did not have the economic capacity to participate and the programs went on. To get to the mentioned programs this year, we had to get funds to cover what the state did not finish," he explained.
Despite there being a promise made by state officials to hand over these resources, he said a request had been sent to Armand Villarreal, Secretary of Administration and Finance, to hasten the proceedings and the corresponding percentages arrived as soon as possible.
"They were supposed to give us 12 million, and although the year is coming to an end, we haven't even gotten a peso yet."
Court Approves 'End of Analogous Broadcasting' in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme State Court (SCJN) rejected a constitutional lawsuit filed by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree, which wants to hasten the so-called "switching off analogous signals" and implement it in 2015 instead of 2021. He stated that the necessary eight votes were not found to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the court, Juan Silva Mezo, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his powers when he issued a decree detailing the steps that would lead to the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the action brought by the Senate was dismissed, because a qualified majority of eight votes needed to allow the court to comment on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the aforementioned decree, which thus remains valid, was not reached.
The draft judgment prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero presents the possibility of declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of all issues related to radio and television is a matter that is reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel). This violates the principles of hierarchical subordination and the exception to the law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted for the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies supported the constitutional dispute in an effort to combat the decree. Minister Sánchez Cordero accepted the demands and suspended the application of the decree and all actions described therein, leading to the transition to digitalization.
The ministerial meeting also decided to reject the action brought by the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion about the proposal, which is also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he does not identify with the arguments of the proposal in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through the general norms of measures to prepare public administration.
"I don't think that even if it did, it would affect the autonomy of the regulator," he said, noting that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive branch, which has a constitutional mandate to determine the direction of the state.
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the biggest changes the world has seen in recent years, linked to better use of the radioelectric spectrum, better signal quality, and more channels.
He believes that delaying change would mean delaying the benefits of digitalisation, which requires public interest decisions, because digitalisation not only has a technical dimension, but also "affects economic, social, political and national security issues".
As he pointed out, these issues "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the state. It includes a number of competences that the Constitution entrusts to the hands of the government of the state".
A number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to a digital system and have done so through their governments, despite having highly specialised technical bodies at their disposal.
He said it was not possible for the government, by issuing a dissenting decree, which to some extent interferes with the powers of Congress, to introduce into the administration compliance with laws prepared by the legislative power.
In Michoacán they analyze the possibility of adding "voice after voice"
According to data published by PREP, the difference between the first and second places in the governor's election is less than 27 percent. So far, 879 votes from 6074 electoral districts have not been counted.
The possibility of counting "vote after vote" appeared in this year's election in Michoacán, where, according to data published by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP), the difference between the first and second places in the governor's election is less than 27 percent, and it has not yet counted 879 votes out of a total of 6074 electoral districts.
In this context, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral authority approved a number of measures that should harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not officially confirm his political constitution or his State Electoral Code or the Electoral Justice Act. The State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the statutory deadline for their entry into force was due to expire in this parliamentary term, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel neglected to publish them within the prescribed deadline in the Act of the Official State Gazette, stating that he had some objections to them.
On November 9, the Supreme State Court (SCJN) settled a constitutional dispute initiated by the local legislative power and declared the head of state's voice on constitutional reforms to be "invalid and illegal" because he has no right to "neither approve nor veto" them.
When asked about the possibility of counting "voice after vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal replied that, thanks to the approval of the relevant measures by the General Council of the IEM, it would be possible for a local electoral authority to carry out a partial and total census.
In this way, partial counting of votes, one or more election packages, will be possible under the following conditions: the election results do not match; there is no record of the vote count and the calculation in the appropriate box or the given chairman does not have it available; or if there have been errors and obvious violations of the election results.
In addition, a total recount of votes in all ballot boxes will be possible if there is evidence to suggest that the difference between the potential winner of the election and the candidate in second place is less than or equal to one percentage point; whenever an explicit request from the party and/or coalition representative who proposed the candidate in second place appears at the beginning of the session.
A total recount will also be possible if, after a proper tally, the difference between the likely winner and the runner-up candidate is found to be equal to or less than one percentage point, and also whenever there is an explicit request from the political party whose candidate finished runner-up. In such a case, the electoral parcels for which a partial tally has been made will be discarded.
It should be noted that in this situation there are elections in Morelia, where according to PREP the difference between the first and second place is less than 0.16%, although 129 of the total 923 electoral districts have not yet been counted.
