The new Italian government will be appointed on Wednesday.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to present him with a new government that will face the crisis that is holding this country above the precipice of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with the Italian president tomorrow to present him with a new government that will face a crisis that is holding the country above the precipice of economic disaster and has put the entire eurozone at risk.
The presidential palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm he could form a government.
It is expected to present a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the president with the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were being overcome.
"The framework is now well marked," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is struggling to combat a political and financial crisis that has brought debt levels to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the tough austerity package demanded by Europe's leaders, only to restore Italy's hacked credibility.
There is a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry, because of market instability, interest rates on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity have exceeded the 7% threshold, a level where Greece and Ireland had to ask for a bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, chairwoman of Confindustria, an Italian employers' organization, told reporters after the meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this burning situation.
Monti's hopes for success have been greatly boosted by the PDL's support for Silvio Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined for good results," Angelina Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because up to now, a number of its members have opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti has put together.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to push for unpopular austerity reforms.
Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure, warning that Monti's failure could spell disaster.
Monti opened talks with political parties, unions and business groups, youth and women's organizations on Monday.
The round will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by President Napolitano, which allowed for a very rapid procedure in response to the crisis.
After a brief decline at the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, interest on Italian bonds returned to a critical level, responding to uncertainty about whether the new prime minister would reap success.
Saving Italy, whose public debt stands at 1.8 trillion euros, would be beyond the scope of the eurozone’s current financial reserves.
Monti said his government should stay in power until the next elections, which are scheduled for 2013, despite general forecasts that politicians will only give him time to carry out reforms and then call early elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that the government must be made up of only experts to take Italy out of the troubles that the country has come into because of financial pressure.
Political sources have said that mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties complicate the attempt to include political figures in the government.
