The quintet included the country in its tour to celebrate 20 years of existence
"A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of the best shows at the National Stadium next Sunday.
We have been waiting for more than 20 years, but the group itself assures that for them the opportunity to play in Costa Rica is a dream come true.
That’s what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively to Viva last week from Brazil, said.
The group is on tour in South America to celebrate 20 years of existence and will be at a unique stop in Central America on Sunday 20th.
On this day, they will perform from 7:30 pm at the National Stadium along with the angel group The X and the national musicians from Las Robertas.
This is a sample of the interview, the full transcript of which can be found on the website of La Nación on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, this is a dream come true. Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica. Do you realize what your fans are experiencing?
Traveling to Costa Rica is also a dream come true.
In South and Central America we are barely the second time and the experience so far has been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation. It's a beautiful country and I believe we will be able to stay here for a few days.
So we are very happy to bring you our music.
I ask because they literally love the band here, the fans are going through these days of preparation very intensely.
What do you say to your worst supporters?
Thank you for standing by us for so many years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long.
Some people refer to the concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that put more pressure on you?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have been over a few weeks.
We did some great shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that we got into shape for a concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to this concert.
We love this country, we love surfing, we like the jungles. For both activities Costa Rica is the best country in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo. The waves here are incredible.
My friends go surfing in Costa Rica or Nicaragua or Mexico. These are the best places to surf. So we learned about Costa Rica through people who love surfing.
If we look at your tour, you have prepared a huge show with many songs.
What are your plans for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played here, we have no limits on what we can't do.
We will try to show the best show with a variety of songs. We will try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why?
I think it’s partly because we have nine albums and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs we play every night.
When we have two or three songs in our repertoire that we haven’t played in a long time, we focus on them and we are surprised because we remember why we liked them so much and that we may have forgotten about it.
That makes the show more interesting for us, and that's why I think it's more interesting for people, too.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of the artistic career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yes, I'm sure.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have imagined being in one big rock band and staying in it for more than 20 years.
We realize how much we have been given and we are moved that we can continue to play together.
We love each other and we love making music.
We’re lucky to be able to see the places we’ve always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were a significant part of the creation of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of greats.
The people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends, it doesn’t happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in a city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to arise from one city at a time.
We are proud to be part of this group from Seattle.
Sometimes we play with others.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored to be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is a lot longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think that, firstly, we are all lucky to be still in this world, and secondly, the fact that we are always interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends and thanks to this we have been able to open musical paths that allow everyone enough freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we value each other’s music, and I don’t think it could be any better.
Your relationship to the word fame has not been easy. However, thanks to your success, you can do what you like.
How do you find balance?
As we grew, it became easier to find balance.
We try not to tour too much because it’s very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people come here for music, you remind yourself that you have to respect the music and what you gave it. You mustn't get carried away by being famous, rock stars. This has never really interested either of us.
What do you think of Mother Love Bone?
I think we were writing great songs and it was something spectacular in the beginning.
As a band, we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that we are still friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in a band with us. When I listen to a song or look at photos, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh with him, talk about music or football.
She was an incredible person and we miss her very much.
The national band Las Robertas will be commissioned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as the opening act?
Yes, the production sent us videos with a few suggestions and we liked this group the most, so we are curious what Las Robertas will offer live and they must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he adds the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influences you as a bassist?
Lots of people.
Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many of them that I could talk all night about bassists that I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge, even though it is no longer in fashion?
I think we've always felt slightly separated from the word grunge.
When I think of grunge, I think of the bands I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana, and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and if that’s how music is today, it’s something great because it’s music that’s worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever.
In the beginning, your music had a slightly gloomy character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
That’s interesting because I feel like there’s a couple of songs in the new album that are lighter in scale, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe that are considered very bleak, although they may sound positive.
For both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried, and they're songs that are deeply dark.
I think when you grow up and you have some trauma in your life, you lose someone in your family or a friend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent just that to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make grim music.
Peru:
Fujimori hospitalised again for medical tests
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized Tuesday in a public hospital where he will be tested for muscle loss in his lower extremities, his attending physician said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving 25 years in prison for human rights abuses committed by his government (1990-2000), suffers from several diseases, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is currently under medical control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, an MP who is his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori will be undergoing tests at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases within three days to find out why he is in pain and why he is losing strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga said that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, however, the former president himself does not want the pardon because he feels innocent.
He was operated on four times for tongue cancer, dropping 18 kilograms, and to these problems were added other ailments such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been serving a sentence since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Police Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people killed by a murderous troop squadron operating illegally in the first years of his rule.
Mujica visits Mexico to strengthen political ties
The official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, accompanied by several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to achieve an expansion of trade between the two nations and to touch on the political issues of the region.
Mujica will meet with her Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón on Wednesday. This is the most important meeting of an extensive visit full of meetings with representatives of politics, business and the Uruguayan community living in Mexico. The program was published by the Uruguayan presidential office.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will serve to exchange information on political matters between the two countries," the Uruguayan presidential office posted on its website.
According to local media, Mujica will try to get Calderón to back Uruguay in a dispute with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened that countries that would continue to be tax havens would be excluded from the international community, a statement that prompted a backlash from Uruguay and consultation with the ambassador to the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November. The G20 is a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries. Since January this year, the Latin American country has concluded an information exchange agreement to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has sought to specify fiscal exchange agreements in order to get off the "blacklist" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), to which there are countries that have not implemented all the required international standards of cooperation in the field of taxation.
Mexico and Uruguay have signed a free trade agreement (FTA) since 2004, which has strengthened the exchange of goods between the two countries.
Bearded plumber runs in 3D thanks to "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for more than 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of villain Bowser, but he has never appeared in 3D: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the love of a girl with stereoscopic technology.
The title, which comes to all stores around the world this month, was created from the beginning to take advantage of all the features offered by the portable Nintendo 3DS console, which allows you to play three-dimensional games without having to use glasses.
"Mario is a character who has to say how stereoscopy should work without glasses," said Omar Álvarez, a press officer specializing in Nintendo in Spain, during a presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "Nintendo's first video game created specifically for this carrier" because up to now successful images like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarina of time 3D" have been adaptations of already existing titles.
A Nintendo spokesperson said that in addition to being 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "available" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and smooth game.
Álvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple", whose task is to attract less skilled users.
Once you overcome this level, you can start the "second round" on the levels of the game, which this time are more challenging.
In addition, users can choose real time between "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. However, it will be necessary to play in 3D in order to overcome various challenges and "do not succumb to optical illusions".
This new arrival of Super Mario in 3D also envisages the return of the character to a portable console, which has not happened since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo plays into the music of those who watch the saga and repeats the successful formula from previous episodes. It consists in the fact that the plumber of the bearded man will have to go through dangerous mined platforms in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find news in moves, surroundings, disguises and also among the enemies, there will also be a "playful" Luigi.
Colom approves extradition of Portillo to the United States
President Álvaro Colom said on Tuesday he had stepped up efforts to extradite former President Alfonso Portillo, who is to be held accountable in the United States for conspiring to launder $70 million.
This is the end of the process to get Guatemala to respond to a request from a northern country demanding the extradition of Portillo in order to judge him.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision is in line with the independence of the judicial and executive powers and that he is mindful that the criminal court has already ordered extradition.
He assured that during his mandate, he did not "interfere" with court decisions and allowed all extraditions that came to his desk.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited for murder and grievous bodily harm, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's move marks a step of execution after all judicial and constitutional instances were exhausted to prosecute a former president who ruled from 2000 to 2004.
In accordance with the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Tribunal and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo will be extradited after his legal situation in Guatemala is resolved and human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was found not guilty of misappropriation of $120 million in the Ministry of Defense at the time of his presidency. This process preceded extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed, putting the case back in the game.
Trinidad helped 6,000 youths in a state of emergency
The organization was created to help children without education, so that they would not find themselves on the fringes of society.
The balance of the first 25 years of the organisation's existence is very important: 6,000 young people at risk of social exclusion have been helped. The organisation has been helping them to overcome difficult situations for 25 years.
To this must be added the long hundreds of jobs that have been obtained for this social group.
Yesterday's anniversary also served to present the balance sheet as part of the ceremony, which took place in the former production premises of both the Fabra and Coats factories and which was attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was founded in the Trinitat Vella district in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with low education, no work, struggling with drug addiction or in a situation where they might fall into social exclusion.
Yesterday’s meeting in Sant Andreu was attended by a large number of representatives of organizations and institutions that have cooperated with the association over the past 25 years.
The diverse political representation, at the time of the elections, showed the uniform nature of the work carried out by Trinijove.
Together with President Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the ceremony was attended by former Socialist Education Advisor, Ernest Maragall, and former Deputy Mayor and current Eco-Socialist Councillor Ricard Goma.
Both Fabra and Coats were joined by the current Social Welfare and Family Adviser, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the Director General of Social Work at La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas said that Trinijove originated in a very difficult time and that today's time also offers a number of obstacles, but added that the work the association has brought to this day "is a good foundation".
The president cited Trinidad as an example of how it is possible to combat adverse circumstances and how to give courage to people in difficult situations.
“The crisis is nothing new to this organization and the work it does,” he said.
There was an eviction of the occupied house, in which gigantic parties were held
Intruders appropriated 11 out of 13 apartments in a building in Balmes, 51
12 occupiers left the house yesterday at noon without resisting
All indications are that the nightmare experienced by the neighbors at 51 Balmes Street is finally over.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building at noon yesterday, where they were illegally occupying and where they were organizing gigantic parties that woke up the neighbors. They left the building by order of the court and without the need for police to intervene.
After the operation, the lock on the door was replaced to prevent a recurrence of the situation.
"From now on, the entrance will be guarded," said the administrator.
The occupiers, who took 11 of the 13 apartments in the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all electrical and partly water equipment, in addition to painting the walls and leaving behind garbage of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the first three apartments huge parties were held, which lasted up to two days and woke up the other tenants.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which was also damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that during the time the building was occupied, sales fell by 80%.
The owner of the disco emphasizes that the occupiers of the building made her unfair competition because they sold drinks for 3 euros, while the disco costs 10 euros.
In addition, the owner of the entertainment company had to respond to complaints from neighbors about noise, but the problems were caused not by visitors to the disco, but by the residents of the occupied house, and especially by those who attended the parties, the frequency and intensity of which has increased in recent weeks, according to the angry residents of the neighborhood.
The owner of the disco explained that the problems were so great that they even agreed with the owner of the building and have been forgiving her rent for nine months.
The city police also confirmed that they had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation in recent weeks.
Last week, Alberto Fernández Díaz, chairman of the PP municipal group in the town hall, demanded that "the building be immediately evicted to put an end to the problems of civil coexistence suffered by neighbors and to the destruction of the area".
The chairman of the People's Party explained that only one floor had been taken before the summer, but in recent months the occupiers had reached all floors of the building and almost all apartments, and in one of them there were even thefts.
He added that "there is a need to put an end to impunity and to be consistent when it comes to acts against civil liability that have occurred in the building."
Yesterday, the city police also cleared the building in Nou Barris.
At 3:30 p.m., police reached building 35 on Mont-ral Street after being summoned by neighbors who saw four people enter the building.
All four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountains?
Architects met on the occasion of the announcement of the proceedings, which brings more than controversy about fees
The 16-gate city competition once again opens the debate on the role of Collserola Park in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the already defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this municipality printed several pamphlets in support of the Collserola Park.
The leaflet defined the mountain as a large park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What’s more, it was supplemented by a numerical comparison with New York’s Central Park.
After the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park returned to the minds of many as the upper limit of Barcelona. The Catalan metropolis is one of the few that are oriented not on the north-south axis, but up (mountain) - down (sea).
The qualification of Collserola as a nature park goes in this direction.
The reference was no longer Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars instead of Yogi Bear.
Such was the position until September, when the town hall announced a mega competition consisting of 16 auditions for the same number of entry gates to Collserola.
The gate, of course, records the idea of the park.
It's either that or someone's trying to place a gate on the field.
So the only question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
During the competition, both in terms of purely organizational and based on reflection on the city, this issue becomes a central theme for all Barcelona architects.
It’s a subject as familiar as when two members of this old caste of chosen ones shake hands in the elevator.
And it was this act that produced one of the rare matches between what three Barcelona architects and pre-university professors thought.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: the selection process is well founded.
According to Roldán, after the question of the side of the bay was raised, "there is also a need" to discuss the "mountain side", so Ildefonso Cerdo's speech about green apples was not followed to the end.
“We have to start from the principle that Barcelona’s largest park is the beach.
Among other things, its high availability.
Collserola is more complex", said the architect, for whom the name "Gateway to Collserola" carries a "lexicological trap": we must not imagine them "as entrances to the park, but rather as demarcation of zones where it is possible to operate".
Modol, as well as Roldán and Bayona with experience in the world of urbanism, qualifies the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The danger resulting from the "uncertainty represented today by the public place project" after the experience of the 1980s, which had "its swansong" in the forum area.
The first concern is the very demarcation of the boundaries where it should be built.
"Defining something means taking the next step", that is, basically taking it a step further.
"New urban planning tools need to be kept in mind, because the current ones (referring to the General Metropolitan Plan (PGM)) can cause a real disaster".
If we focus on the question in more detail, Modol believes that the valley slope of Collserol can be "considered a park", but the Barcelona part is not, for purely topographical reasons.
Modol also recalled that there is already work done by the Patronat de Collserola, which "must not end up in the dump", although he welcomes the fact that the town hall is offering his Bureau to intervene in the project from "the first moment".
Moreover, he understands that the proximity of the mountain and the city is a sort of pass that allows architects to engage in the debate, but he "does not doubt" that it should be precisely this technical profile that will lead the multidisciplinary teams ("it's all about skills", he adds) that need to be created: "Architects should only be tools".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gave the name to this game is complex, as Collserol's global vision for the selection process is lacking: "16 tenders have been announced that deal with all the axis of the mountain - the sea, but there is no longitudinal study that looks at the area and understands it as a whole".
This causes him, at least, to apply to all 16 selection procedures.
Otherwise, the design of a single gate may hint at the concept and definition of the architect of a neighboring gate.
In his view, the City Hall should guarantee that the zone immediately above Ronda de Dalt should provide a full-length zone of equipment to ensure a smooth transition between the city and the greenery.
Casino Pardons Jonas Larrazábal, Who Will Be Released
After 72 days in prison, Cadino Red granted a pardon to Mayor Monterrey's brother in a trial in which he was prosecuted for alleged extortion.
Manuel Jonás Larrazábal spent 72 days in prison and will now be released after being pardoned by Casino Red's legal representative before the District's Second Criminal Court, which was hearing a case of extortion in which Monterrey's brother was indicted.
After the Casino Royale assassination, Casino Red owner Sergio Gil García posted a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonás was asked to pay an economic quota to allow the Monterrey City Hall to operate illegally in the betting house.
After the public prosecution, the State Prosecutor's Office launched a criminal prosecution against the brother of the Panist mayor.
Then, after spending 4 hours in front of Public Ministry Agent Number 3 for property crimes, he was transferred to Prison 1, located in Barrio Antiguo in the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days after the second incarceration order was passed and a Public Ministry agent disproved the possibility of complicity or organized crime.
On 19 October, he was transferred to the Cadereyta Criminal Court on suspicion of extortion of the owners of Casino Red by the sum of one and a half million pesos. However, he remained only a few hours in a medium-duty prison as he was threatened with death.
Leaders allowed him to stay in the city cells in San Nicolás de los Garza during the trial.
On October 25, he was presented with an arrest warrant issued by the Second Criminal Court's secretary, Jorge Yánez, who stated that after nearly two months of investigation, enough evidence had been collected to prove Jonas' guilt. Evidence includes, for example, the payment of a sum of 1.5 million pesos to casino representatives in exchange for a promise that the operation would be allowed.
This Monday, Casino Red’s legal representative, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went to Judge José Luis Pecin and asked for mercy for the region’s mayor’s brother, and on that basis, he will soon be able to return to freedom.
During the legal hearing, a Public Ministry representative assigned to this court, Ramiro Arias, asked García Gómez if the damages had been repaired and who among the associates decided to grant a pardon, but the lawyer made it clear that the name would remain secret.
On the basis of the official file 197/2011, a legal pardon is granted to Jonas Larrazábal. No complaint will be made in the process conducted against him. It is also not possible to claim damages or punishment.
After a trial with a legal representative at around 15:50, the court ordered the immediate release of Larrazábal Breton.
The court secretary, Jorge Yanez, arrived at the prison in San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been granted an official pardon and his case had been postponed to the archives.
He was also informed that the judge had issued an immediate order for his release.
Dionisio Pérez Jacome, the secretary of state, presented details of the plane crash that killed the governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven other people.
The Communications and Transport Secretariat (SCT) said the results of an investigation into the crash that killed Cabinet Secretary Francisco Blake Mora and seven others showed the helicopter hit the ground with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt a forced landing.
Speaking at a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jacome, Secretary for Communications and Transport, said that before the flight, the pilot stated that climatic conditions allow the flight.
"Parts appearing indicate the unit came into contact with the terrain several times, wings tangled in tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost its hull".
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met all the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that based on an investigation conducted in the area of impact, no components were found on the ground.
"In the search, it was found that the parts of the plane were not located in another place, so the plane hit the land as a whole.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, it met all the requirements for passenger transport.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that the most important thing at the moment is to get the results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, stated that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was moving at cruise speed and the accident occurred on soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that this was a normal overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At the press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jacome listed six basic points of the investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, that is, the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the AICM indicate adequate conditions at launch, accordingly, the aircraft is advancing towards the border, between the DF and the State of Mexico were noticeable layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility as far as the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the helicopter from the radar coincide, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the trajectory of the flight before the impact.
Dispersion of aircraft remnants within a restricted area:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A sketch of the aircraft's debris scattering indicates that at the time of impact on land, the helicopter was intact.
There was no fire or explosion.
No evidence was recorded at the scene of the disaster that there had been an explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During fieldwork, the remains of the aircraft were found at an altitude of up to 9,200 feet above sea level, the terrain slopes, the height of the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photos show footage that likely disintegrated along the route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search in the vicinity of the accident, in a territory larger than the area of demarcation, the remains of the helicopter were not found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state where the helicopter was still intact.
Mexican Institute of Health Insurance Launches Research into Gene That Causes Obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity in children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the IPN Institute
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. Research called "Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents" will allow to get results related to overweight.
In a report, the head of the Medical Biochemistry Research Unit at the National Medical Center’s 21st Century Specialized Hospital, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been established.
This team relies on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The general public, with or without authorization, can also participate in the research. People can come to the participating IMSS sports centers in Valle de México, where they will be tested for juveniles from 8 a.m.
He pointed out that the research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Center (Mexican State) and since 8 October, this activity has also been carried out at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Center (East of Mexico State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children has been obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and eventually at the Morelos Sports Center (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the goal of this research is to determine the components and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to track down risk factors in Mexican children and young people, thereby preventing the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
To mark International Diabetes Day on November 14, he said the goal is to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with parental consent and supervision, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are made anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels are determined, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes that are involved in the development of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the research reflects health officials' concerns about the alarming increase in baby weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77% increase in obesity among boys and 47% among girls. There was a dramatic increase also in overweight,' said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Native American genetic makeup, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in the genes that are responsible for the development of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) that is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the participants’ direct benefit was that they received an overall assessment of the children’s condition to see if they showed any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of dark-colored wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-diabetes conditions.
For now, the information is confidential, with doctors writing to parents explaining all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make to help their children avoid illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three main ingredients that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that implies a lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV all day, and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also caused by a large caloric intake, i.e. a greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asphalt from UNAM there will be no potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, creates modified asphalts with polymers, creating a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature.
Nearly 200,000 potholes would not need to be repaired after each rainy season in the Valle de México metropolitan area if the pavements were properly cared for, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a scientist at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavements were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even a complete elimination of them.
In his lecture, Technological Cause of Potholes, which he delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, which should create a mixture with similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and at high temperatures.
Herrera Nájera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve functionality and reduce pothole formation.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is an assembly of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules of high molecular weight called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight called maltenes. Together, they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic character of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees it has a high viscosity, and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but varies during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, a chemical engineering expert has warned.
A scientist from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Mexico City are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the uppermost layers is an asphalt insert, made up of small pebbles embedded in the asphalt and then compressed.
He stressed that every stone that makes up the liner is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure, it is possible to distribute the forces in the pavement well.
If it was modified asphalt, it would decompose even better, according to a chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer, called the shell, is placed on the asphalt insert, consisting of fine stone, i.e. sand also embedded in the asphalt.
Since this layer will come into contact with the rims of vehicles, it must have a greater mechanical force than the asphalt insert and must provide friction to the roadway.
Since it will be exposed to heavy loads as part of the paving, the shell must be of sufficient thickness and care must be taken of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to keep in mind. In particular, water has a great effect on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is moist, the water spreads inwards and it is hard to get out, this causes all the paving layers to soften and thus create potholes.
He explained that when potholes are created, the film of the shell is damaged first and only then the asphalt liner is damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one time, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first signs with the help of appropriate maintenance programs.
As a member of the National System of Scientists, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of pavement must correspond to the load on vehicles and ensure that this load is not exceeded. This is the only way to prevent frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to be done when it comes to asphalt, and research is at the beginning. For example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries, make it easy to repair potholes without having to use high temperatures, are worth mentioning.
