This was the work of a Cali resident who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A fingerprint expert from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4 last year, a fingerprint expert from the CTI in Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the Supreme Leader of Farc: "Alfonse Cana", through a fingerprint comparison.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working in the CTI department, it was Eliazar González, a Puerta Tejada man who has been working in forensic research for 21 years, this week.
Early in his career, González worked at Chocó Town Hall, where he often had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to a place where there were corpses that needed to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to the capital, Valle, and after completing the relevant courses, he began to specialize in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of rubbing the skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
In the week of the operation against the aforementioned Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to take his clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night, he set off for Cauco in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he would have to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who led the world's oldest guerilla, so they asked him to take a fingerprint card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigating team at the location of the body, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a villager in the area, without glasses, much slimmer.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Along with the galton magnifier, ink and transplanter, and light, Eliazar began to compare the dactyl records of the corpse with those of the card.
The eye did not disappoint him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, a man originally from Puerto Tejada was commissioned to confirm to the Secretary of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, whether he was indeed the Commander-in-Chief of Farc.
Search for tracks
For the dactyloscope from Sijin de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos showed to Eliazar González at the press conference of the operative service against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, which can play a key role in the decision-making of crimes.
In addition to identifying corpses, these people assist in researching crimes such as theft or murder, and confirm the identity of the persons caught.
When caught, a lot of delinquents present fake papers or don't have papers at all.
We'll take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator related that in case of injury, he had to remove a piece of the wall of the house, because in this place the thief was leaning to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not designed to take fingerprints, but in this case we could get a full handprint and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also confirm or refute suspicions in a murder case.
Recently, a man was found dead with bottles of alcohol around him.
The investigation revealed that one of the family members could be responsible for the murder, and the print on the bottle actually confirmed this.
Although it cannot be 100% confirmed that he was indeed a murderer, it is clear that he appeared on the scene of the crime.
A fingerprint expert from the CTI explained that the objects are "wiped away with chemical or physical reactive agents."
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to collect them.
After that, the prints are sent to Asif, which is a database of delinquents, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians whose data are not recorded anywhere," said a CTI expert.
He explained that not everything is as it appears on the CSI television program.
Just like everything that glitters is not gold, not everything you touch leaves traces.
However, if it can be used, an appropriate comparison must be made.
