The Golden Rule on Balanced Budgets
The government of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write a "golden rule" of budget policy into the constitution to reduce the public deficit and avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's rating agencies (AAAs).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the close of the ministerial meeting, in a situation where Austria’s public debt is 74.6% above the criteria of no more than 60% set by the Maastricht Agreement, but much lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If Austria’s solvency were reduced by just one degree from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros more in interest each year,” said Michael Spindelegger, vice chancellor and foreign minister.
Austria follows up on the request of the Euro Summit held in Brussels on 26 October 2011, where the heads of state and government strongly requested that by the end of 2012, the reduction of the public deficit and the achievement of the balance of public accounts be written in the constitution or in the law of equal value.
The instrument adopted by the Austrian government is approaching the "German model", Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the public structural deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) every year, and starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal state will not be allowed to exceed 0.35% of GDP every year, while the Länder, as well as the municipalities, will have to report a balanced budget.
The aim is to bring public debt below the 60% target set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/21.
