Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is one subject that cannot be grasped on the basis of short-term balance sheets or under emotions, it is energy policy.
Electricity availability and price have a direct impact on purchasing power and business competitiveness.
It is natural for an election meeting to be an opportunity to think about such deposits and a place that takes energy from the core.
The debate will only succeed if all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options are examined.
The French must base their position on objective facts and rational data.
So far, there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, but demographic developments will cause a doubling of the demand for electricity between now and 2050 if we do not want to deprive a significant part of the world’s population of an important part of life.
At the same time, there will have to be a shortage of fossil fuels in order to continue to produce electricity, while not forgetting the need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a topic that is currently disappearing from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not affect any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to reject nuclear power.
But this is not the case in Belgium, which is subjecting its decision to the need to find some other source capable of replacing itself, nor in Switzerland, which considers it right to build only the latest generation power plants.
In contrast, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to quote at least some countries, continue with determination in their projects.
After Fukushima, the United States decided to expand its park by one unit by resuming the construction of one power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island power plant disaster.
If the German renewable energy model is ever presented as an example, reality contradicts it.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on gas imported mainly from Russia, a sharp increase in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of natural gas and coal-fired power plants.
All these unpleasant effects will be felt within a few months.
The case of Denmark deserves us to think about it.
The European wind power champion, of which it consumes 30% of its electricity, is also one of the largest consumers of coal and gas due to wind irregularities, which makes CO2 emissions and prices of Danish electricity higher by 65% and 50%, respectively, than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the immutability of our energy policy, our neighbours will pay an electricity bill 40% higher than the payment of French households.
While in a globalised economy energy costs are a key factor for competitiveness and a guarantee of keeping industry on national territory, French businesses enjoy the benefits of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would trigger a strong increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory beautiful declarations about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
The price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay, just as they do not fundamentally oppose this energy, as opinion polls show.
Let us recall that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 downstream jobs.
The strong export sector has attracted a large number of small and medium-sized specialised enterprises to international markets, creating jobs that cannot be transferred abroad.
If France had decided to leave the nuclear power plant, it would have sacrificed a considerable number of these small and medium-sized enterprises and would have lost 6 billion euros a year, which the country receives for exporting nuclear equipment and services.
Which power plant owner would order a nuclear reactor designed to operate for 60 years while its manufacturer was scheduled to go bankrupt?
When solving the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no magic source for energy production, and even that there is no diabolical one.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable energy installations by the French industrial group AREVA testifies to the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear power, it is absolutely necessary to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have the State Office for Nuclear Safety, which carries out uncompromising and transparent supervision over existing nuclear power plants as well as the construction of a new power plant in Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, have the idea of safety in the blood.
In 50 years, the nuclear industry has seen three major accidents.
The only one in Three Mile Island occurred in normal conditions of operation and remained free of human sacrifice and environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the drama was caused by reactor concepts and inexcusable human errors.
In the case of Fukushima, some seem to forget that the crash was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will take lessons from this crash, just as it did with the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step, and of the cooperation between the French and German nuclear safety authorities, operators and designers, is that an EPR reactor is a concept capable of resisting such phenomena.
While everyone who wishes to build a nuclear power plant considers it, halting its construction in Flamanville would be an excellent gift offered to AREVA Group and EDF’s competitors and freeing the way for them to take a leading position in nuclear development.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best energy solution for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and machinations dominate the debate so crucial to our country’s economic, social and financial situation.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various angles - the congestion of the police, the courts and the administration subjected to the politics of numbers, the compatibility of this policy with the status of the "land of human rights" that France boasts.
More recently, it was an administrative harassment directed at foreign students that became topical when the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of May 23) said that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and waitresses".
But so far, it has rarely been discussed at the angle of the economy.
There is a broad consensus between the left and the right in this area.
Jacques Chirac declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country where there are 2 million immigrant workers" and on the left Michel Rocard, saying in 1990 that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of invasion by hordes of Polish plumbers into French territory was shared to the right and to the left.
In both camps, immigrants are seen as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that we deign to give to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande confines himself to banalities when he states that joint development will make it possible to solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem may be valid in elections, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in their recently published work synthesizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.): there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration movements on economic growth, wages, and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
Reducing immigration cripples growth and hurts employment.
Concerns about the effects caused by migrants are based on the idea that these people can replace French workers, especially the less skilled, and put pressure on them to lower their wages.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are much more of a top-up than substitutes for French workers by doing jobs in understaffed sectors.
Low-skilled immigrants in sectors that do not attract French workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where education is not enough to offer jobs.
Positive impact on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, these additions between French and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of French workers.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration movements would cause a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And it does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay, and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to welfare systems in European countries, averaging 1% of the total budget.
For example, the World Labor Organization estimates that in Germany, one immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will bring a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of ?150,000 to public budgets in his or her lifetime.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy expressed his desire to go for the missing percentage of growth “with his teeth out.”
The teeth used to repel immigrants had the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought through
Democracy is a rare and very fragile commodity.
The European continent should remember this, for even though it was invented in Athens two thousand years ago, it experienced the tragedies of world wars, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulags, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, and the colonels in Greece during the 20th century.
Some people may have believed that it would be enough to make the choice and carry it out in the most direct way possible for democracy to triumph over its enemies.
Napoleon knew that it was easy to think.
Universal suffrage, even if it is a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition and can become "an instrument of oppression," as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization of separation and control by power, education, enlightenment, social and economic solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as and from the beginning of the crises of politics and democracy.
Admitting the error of the Greek yes-no referendum will have the value of a double revelation in this respect: the revelation of the need for a major return to political power, but also the revelation of a disturbing sense of its impossibility, its unsuitability.
This ambivalence must be thought through in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the Democratic struggle have shifted today, and that many of the Republican fighters are no longer firing in the right direction.
We cannot gain anything if we demand a series of national referendums organised according to necessity and disorganised.
Bianka exposed to a European absolute monarch or a leap with bound feet into the empty nationalist depths: what a choice for a citizen!
No, we do not want guillotine knives, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - nor would we know where to stop - because the crisis is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its incompetence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is being humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty and with it each of its peoples.
The management of the European project of democratic sovereignty must be returned as a matter of urgency.
For only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, get rid of market government and prepare the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will presuppose decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, otherwise it would lead us to disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today is strongly demanding a European economic government.
Fair enough.
But to think so without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new impasse.
We must take on a new phase of European construction.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to "be" republicans.
A revolution in interests was not enough.
This lesson continues.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a Europe of more politically democratic and genuine European democratic sovereignty.
Let us become Europeans to build Europe.
