Nord Stream, the new port of entry for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and running along the bottom of the Baltic Sea began to work.
It must supply gas equal to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to properly celebrate the event.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of Nord Stream last Tuesday, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned the control valve around to control Russian gas entering the Western European grid.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow into Western Europe each year through the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with the state of Mecklenburg-Pomorania.
The second pipeline, which must be completed by the end of 2012, will supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, an amount equal to all French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route is already being mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building has the character of a victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly objected to the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being routed by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
All of a sudden, these two countries are losing some of their power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats to close its access to Western European markets becomes more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most forcefully when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means that it is a politically sensitive issue.
Western Europe, through its support for this Russian project, has gained greater certainty in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe’s energy, because the project has created rifts between Europeans from the East and the West.
Only five years ago, Russia managed to impose its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich, gas-intensive Western states, whose deposits are coming to an end.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us,” Fillon confirmed at the opening ceremony of the pipeline, demonstrating at what point the big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The undersea pipeline is made of steel fitted with a concrete sheath to protect it from anchors of naval vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid minefields originating from the time of World War II.
“For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Muller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers, which is not interrupted anywhere by valves or maintenance stations.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project managers rejected it when the Swedes were little eager to see the Russian state-owned company settle permanently off their shores.
"In the event of a fault, we will stop the passage of gas in less than 1 minute," says Jens Muller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline leaks into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since the welds were designed so that the leak would occur once every 100,000 years.
The control of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
At the destination, after a full three-day journey at a speed of 3 m/s, it will provide accurate information on possible deformations of the metal parts.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom's leading position is holding a 51% stake.
It was joined by the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch company Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
The five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company for five years with a contract, which can be renewed, all of its gas transportation capacity.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Mäller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided from 30% by shareholders and from 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs soared to $240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be reimbursed, because only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
Valves 4.5 meters high form the gas exit gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to German gas pipelines.
As of last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, this will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - branded notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded 50 years ago, wants to once again provide the joy of writing.
It brings the smell of adventure, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable by its black rectangular plates and its leaves of faded white color, as if aged over time.
After all, the Moleskine notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, will at that time decide to launch a new design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes charge of the launch of a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (skin imitation), which is used, for example, to modify the surface of benches.
This type of notebook was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought back an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand’s leader at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose 26% to settle at 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is distant from the secret production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create an artificial portrait of the buyer, as the notebook will attract businessmen as well as students or professionals.
The image of Moleskine's notebook includes that its owners are people of cosmopolitan, cultivated and open spirit.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, now has almost a hundred, and since 2008 it has two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to bookstores and, through the FNAC chain of stores, to small boutiques in the middle of cities, where he has been able to assert his identity.
“We have been following the spirit of the times and this need for new writing, through the tumultuous development of e-mails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition "Zacházka", where architects or artists exhibit their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also presented new scrapbook records resembling a leopard.
Moleskine benefits from its success and this cultural aura, diversifying its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases ... The brand extends to a wide range of carriers.
A success that aroused envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment funds of SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is there such a high proportion of unemployed disabled workers?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today marks the 15th week of employment for the disabled.
Despite the voluntarist public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed disabled persons is even twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it disheartening?
"No, underscores Éric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt Association, which organizes the Week for the Employment of the Handicapped".
"The progress made in 15 years is remarkable."
"At the time, the percentage of unemployed was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, there is still much to be done."
It must be said that many obstacles remain for the unemployed disabled before they start working.
These are elderly people: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They are low-skilled: 80% do not have a high school diploma, and of the 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% among the disabled compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to work and which constitute the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, which was founded in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There remain unsaid ways of thinking that certainly evolve, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that executives surveyed had a "weak level of knowledge about disabled people" with an "over-imagination of people on a wheelchair and psychological or mental deficiencies".
As a result, private businesses with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the 6% employment goal for disabled workers set out in the 1987 law.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, indicate a status equal to 2.6%.
“We’re now at around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization charged with charging businesses that don’t comply with the law.
This is evidenced by the number of "punished" businesses, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 offenders between 2007 and 2011 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses, Pierre Blanc explains."
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Labor Department, only 59% of businesses with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of businesses with 100 to 199 employees.
